Of course, this equals $\frac{z}{1 + z^2} + \frac{z^2}{1 + z^4} + \frac{z^3}{1 + z^6}$. Clearly $z^7 = 1$ and $z \ne 1$. So,
\begin{align*}
\frac{z}{1 + z^2} + \frac{z^2}{1 + z^4} + \frac{z^3}{1 + z^6} &= \frac{z + z^4 - z^4 - z^6}{1 + z}
\\&= \frac{z + z^4}{1+z} -
\frac{z^3 + z^5 - z^3 - z^5}{1+z}
\\
&= \frac{z(1 + z^3) - z^3 (1 + z^3)}{1 + z} 
\\
&= (1-z^3) \left( \frac{z}{1+z} \right) 
\\
&= \left( \frac{(1-z) (1 + z + z^2)}{1+z} \right) \left( \frac{z}{1+z} \right)
\\
&= \frac{z (1-z)(1+z)}{1+z} 
= \frac{z(1-z)}{1+z} = \frac{z - z^2}{1+z} .
\end{align*></think> <answer>$\frac{2 \sin\left(\frac{4 \pi}{7}\right)}{2 \cos\left(\frac{4 \pi}{7}\right) + 1}$</answer>

